            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ricardo Santos is a San Francisco native, a distinction he wears with quiet pride. Born and raised in the fog-belt of the Excelsior District, he is the son of Filipino immigrants. His father worked as a janitor for the city and his mother as a hotel housekeeper, their lives a testament to grueling work for modest pay. Ricardo\u2019s name, a legacy of Spanish colonial history in the Philippines, often surprises people, a detail he\u2019s grown accustomed to explaining.\n\nIn school, Ricardo was more interested in the social ecosystem of the hallways than in academics. He was bright but unfocused, graduating with a general studies diploma and no clear path forward. For a few years, he drifted between retail jobs, feeling the city he loved become increasingly unaffordable around him. The turning point was his grandmother\u2019s, his *Lola\u2019s*, prolonged illness. Ricardo became a primary caregiver, discovering an unexpected well of patience and compassion within himself. He found deep meaning in providing comfort, a purpose that had been missing.\n\nMotivated, he earned his Certified Nursing Assistant (CNA) license. He didn't want the sterile environment of a hospital; instead, he found his calling with the San Francisco Unified School District, working as a one-on-one aide for students with severe developmental disabilities. It\u2019s demanding work that perfectly suits his calm demeanor and physical resilience.\n\nHis daily routine is a familiar rhythm. An early alarm, then the 4.5-mile commute on the 29-Muni bus from his small, shared apartment in the Excelsior to a school near Golden Gate Park. His social life revolves around lifelong friends, pickup basketball games at Crocker-Amazon Park, and Sunday dinners with his parents. He is deeply connected to his neighborhood, lamenting the closure of old family-owned shops but still loving its unpretentious, multicultural energy.\n\nRicardo dreams of stability. He\u2019s saving diligently and taking prerequisite courses at City College, hoping to one day enter the Registered Nurse (RN) program. His aspiration isn\u2019t wealth, but the ability to buy a small condo in the city that holds his entire history, securing his place in the ever-changing landscape of San Francisco."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, his small hand lost in his father\u2019s calloused one, walking down Mission Street on a foggy Saturday morning. The neon sign of 'Star-Bread' glowed, promising the warm, yeasty smell of *pan de sal*. His dad, tired from his janitor shift but smiling, bought them a bag. That simple walk\u2014the rumble of the 14-Mission bus, the taste of home\u2014cemented the Excelsior as his entire world. It\u2019s the feeling of belonging he\u2019s been chasing ever since.\n\n2.\nHe recalls the quiet rhythm of spooning warm *lugaw* into his Lola\u2019s mouth during her final months. Her words were gone, but her frail hand would squeeze his, a flicker of recognition in her clouded eyes. In those silent afternoons, the air thick with love and medicinal herbs, Ricardo discovered a profound purpose. It wasn't about healing; it was about presence and comfort. The experience, happening in his early twenties, planted the seed of compassion that would define his career and his understanding of strength.\n\n3.\nIn his first year as an aide, he was assigned a non-verbal student prone to agitated outbursts. For weeks, Ricardo simply sat near him, a calm, steady presence. One afternoon, after a difficult morning, the boy stopped rocking. He looked at Ricardo, truly locked eyes, and placed his small hand on Ricardo\u2019s arm. There were no words, but the message was immense: *I trust you*. That quiet touch affirmed that this demanding work wasn't just a job; it was his true calling.\n\n4.\nLast week at Crocker-Amazon, playing pickup with the same guys he\u2019d known since middle school, he made a no-look pass for an easy layup. The play was followed by laughter and familiar, friendly trash talk. In that moment of breathless camaraderie under the hazy sky, the weight of his financial worries briefly lifted. This was his other family, his other home. This easy, shared history was a type of wealth the city\u2019s new arrivals could never buy, and a powerful reason to fight to stay.\n\n5.\nOne evening last semester, the 29-Muni groaned up the hill from school, his anatomy textbook open on his lap. He looked up as the bus crested the slope, revealing the city lights twinkling below a blanket of fog. For a moment, the exhaustion of his long day vanished. He felt like a part of the city\u2019s circulatory system\u2014a quiet, essential traveler on a familiar route. This small view, this persistent journey, hardened his resolve. He would not be pushed out of the home he saw from this window."
